We're trying hard here [to retain it], because we want- we want a child's education to be complete.
IC.people are trying their hardest for themselves
If [the students] study it well, they will get it back.
But they go outside [the class] and they forget again, then they speak English again.
Let me compare [them] to a White [student I once had].
Niineyei3eihini' nuhu' co'ouutou3oot, hii3iihi' wo3onohuut, toh'etneyeitii3i'.

I had just started teaching [this group of students];
I told them “this is how far you need to learn [for the next class]”
Heetniikookokoh'ouP kokoh'outii3i' heetniisiini neyeitii3i' hinono'einihiit, heenee3etouuse' nuhu' hinono'einihiit.
They were to study- they were to study how to read some Arapaho words, [learn] the sounds of some Arapaho words.
Well then later, later, on Saturday, [the student] came back.
Hee, heneecee boh'ooo, neneeninoo (nih'oo3ounni'ii3etit) Reed Tetter, ni'ii3oo3i'.
Hi, Buffalo Bull Thunder, I am (he gave his name in English) Reed Tetter, (that's what they called him.)

he had just started learning for the first time, and that's what [he managed to do].

Well the Arapahos were all sitting there, [and heard how good the White women were doing], then they really made an effort;
They didn't want to be beat by a White person.

Long ago folks only spoke Arapaho.
When they played together, they would be speaking Arapaho to each other.
But today I hear the children, they only speak English.
You all [in this class] are going to study it very carefully,
you're going to study carefully, the different inflections [lit. 'sounds'] of the Arapaho words.
Nonoohobe3en, nonoohowun, nonoohowo', nonoohobe3enee, nonoohowoti, nonoohobei'eenee, nonoohobei3i', heetniiseeneesee3etouuse'.
I see you, you see me, I see him, I see you all, you see them, you all see us, he sees them, all the various ways a word can change.
Toonheeneti3o', wo'ei3 heebeheeneti3oo hiite'eihiiP 3i'oku3i', cebxo'oeP cebisee3i':
Whomever I'm speaking to, or you might want to speak to some folks sitting here [next to you], [other folks] are walking by:
'Yes, I know them,' [they might answer], and so forth.
[You also need to learn] the prefixes [lit. 'how the sound starts'].
Then you'll have grown into [using the language fully].
grow up to reach a point
Nototii, hotii, nototii, hototii, hitotiiw, hitotiibinoo, bisiitotiibiitoonin, heenei'isiihi'.
My car, car, my car, your car, his car, their car, all of us guys' cars, and so forth.
[You'll eventually learn] the order of the different prefixes.
Hiniito'eibetiit, neeneisinihiitooni' hiniito'eibetiit: neinoo, neisonoo, nei'eibehe', nebesiibehe', neehebehe', heenei'isiihi', nehei, nesi.
The family, the ways you describe the family: my mother, my father, my grandmother, my grandfather, my younger siblign, and so forth, my aunt, my uncle.
And there are words for all these things.
You will- you will know them.
There are many words for where we are, for where we live.
First of all there are words for... [the places] have names.
??? the stream which flows past here, on downstream.
Well over there on the other side of the hill, that big stream [Big Wind River] flowing that way, it has a name.
Over there after it [flows] through the reservoir [Big Wind River becomes Bighorn River after flowing through Boysen Reservoir].
HeeneiP kox3i': hooxono'oo, cee'eyeino'oowu', xonouu'oo', koonootoohoene', boo'oowu', sosoni'.
Over the hill: Riverton, Ft. Washakie, Thermopolis, Arapaho Ranch, Hudson, Shoshoni.
You will use all those names.
And right here there's Arapahoe, Ethete, and so forth.
You all can name all the places [in Arapaho], wherever you go.
Keep [these names] firmly in your mind;
You will hold on to them tightly. [tei'- strong > tou' ?]
That's how you will finally learn them.
you don't do it, you won't [learn them].
Well slowly the Arapaho language is being killed off.
we learn it first now as we move into the future.
Our own language is laying back there behind us in the past.
We are strong through the Arapaho language, wherever we come together.
It's good that- now our culture is strong [if we have Arapaho back].
Nenee' hinee beh'eihehi' heeneicooniini, Nenee' hinee hotii, 'oh hu'un ce'einox, beh'eihehi'.
That Old Man Flat Pipe, That Sacred Wheel, and that Old Man Sacred Medicine Bundle.
Well Old Man Peyote; Well Old Man Peyote;
Then there are the Four Old Men, they occupy the Four Ceremonial Positions.
This Reservation, we are protected here.
[The Sacred Ones] know where our culture is heading;
Even though things are becoming more like the Whites, the Old Man, who has been sitting there since long ago, is still there.
He has been with us since the beginning right up to the present.
It was very hard for us to make it to this point;
how get to here/how make it through
at first we had to go to war [to preserve our life].
Here it is, He is still with us through all this, he is still caring for us.
Now we've got to take back the Arapaho language.
You all talk to Him, talk to Him, ask Him that life be good.
Friendship...that will- Sacred Wheel...that's how you will walk from here towards the future.
Wohei beebeet nih'iisinihii-noo, hii3eti' niiyou nuhu' nih'oo3ouniihi', tousooxe3iini'.
Well just like I said, this White man way is good, that's how it has to be. ???

[if] he knows [the White way of life] then he gets a job.
If not, then it's difficult, the way jobs are today.
That's where the White man's way of life is useful [to you]:
It's really different [from our old ways] too:
niihi'neeniihi' he'ne'ini cebxootiini' niiyou nuhu' he3ebiini.
now everyone is moving rapidly towards the future.

they started studying it for a while, several years.

'oh huut, wootii yiihoono' hinee niitohnonih'ino' heteenetiitoonin.

If you know it you just speak it any time you want.
If you don't know it, you're going to be stuck with [only] English.
Today when folks speak Arapaho, they're half speaking English [already].
That's how it is when they speak Arapaho.
In the end they're only going to be speaking English.
You kids, you students, don't quit!
that's what the old men said.

Only [through Arapaho will you fully express] family, love, respect, honoring that's what our language is about.
You will all pick up on it.

This is what I have to say to you all.
